Comment:
for those wondering why they are using swords thousands of years into the future:

0:49 most people carry these personal shields on them. they completely deflect any fast moving projectiles. guns are obsolete, but there are beam energy weapons called Lasguns, which are somewhat common. however, they arent widely used because a Lasgun beam hitting a personal shield triggers a massive explosion (pretty much nuclear). so both people would die. 

This led to a unique blade fighting style where you must move your blade slowly enough to enter the shield, but fast enough to outsmart your opponent.


Dune is full of stuff like this, i love it


edit: read the first book. i promise you, if you find this kind of thing interesting you will love the world frank herbert created. it's hard at first to read and understand, but is the best fiction i've ever read

¬†@Azakadune¬† One of my biggest fears about dying are all my favorite series like Star Trek, and Doctor Who, and wondering what the next episode or next series or next movie will be about. Comment: You aren't alone. My dad passed the week that Dune part 1 came out and unfortunately we were not able to see it together. Needless to say that sitting in our local IMAX Dome Theater with dual laser projectors and Dolby Atmos sound with an 80 foot screen it was an overwhelming experience, but I am certain my sobbing when Duke Leto dies could be felt if not heard throughout the theater. Much like Paul's father my father's death was unexpected. My parents introduced me to the Universe of Dune back in 1979 when I was 9 years old. I was an old soul and a gifted Avid Reader of anything I could get my hands on. Much like my father even at that age the more challenging and complex something was the more likely we were to be interested in it. Just days before he died we talked about going to see this recent adaption and how excited we were largely driven by this particular trailer using the music of Pink Floyd was driving us. In many ways I think this trailer was better than the following two movies we got not saying something because they are incredible. That said I would like to see Paul Atreides Water of Life scene in part 2 redone with a one-off Pink Floyd song much like Brian Eno did the prophecy theme in the original 84 production surrounded by wonderful music by Toto. I love Hans Zimmer's scores don't get me wrong as I consider them to be some of the greatest ever produced, but this scene in the film was downplayed to an extent that it really needed something to have it stand apart from the rest. However we will always have this trailer and if that's all my dad got to see that I know he was happy with what it seemed that we would be getting and I would say that it's close enough. I consider this trailer to be one of Paul's dreams that he dreams would come true.
author: @mikalmos369

Comment:
Do you want it to wait a year in post-production until consumers are willing to sit in a crowded theater? There's denying that fact, or at least subverting it. Art is a product of its time: if Dune 2021 is good enough that all of us lament watching it at home and pining for what was lost, then Dune is even better. But if we forget it then Dune is a book or a high budget TV series but NEVER a movie, as people have said and capable artists have struggled against since it was written. 

Dune is probably not for a general audience, because in it a hero causes a jihad, it grows beyond him and causes a religion, it outlives him and consumes his son, and his son consumes the sandworms and alters our evolution forever over the course of four thousand years. This beautiful world's attempt to coexist with the modern world is embodied within them calling the spread of Paul's Zensunni Fremen forces beyond Arrakis a Crusade instead of a Jihad (as in the original very western text), so if this thing doesn't put butts in seats then I think it's on them the creators and not the distributors making life or death decisions about the medium.

Comment: ¬†@truantray¬† Actually, the extended version (shown only on TV) of Lynch's film was much better because it explained so much more. The sad thing was that he actually filmed every significant scene in the book, and the combined footage ran over 9 hours if I remember correctly, which was then cut down to what was finally released to theaters. It's a shame there's no way to see it all. What we saw in theaters had huge shortcomings in what was portrayed (Baron Harkonen, the Guild navigator, the weirdling modules, prana bindu fighting, etc.), but it also had some great strengths (the cast, the music, the surreal imagery while transforming the Water of Life, The Voice used by the Bene Gesserit, shield fighting, the Shai Huluud, etc.). If we could have seen the entire story as originally filmed, Lynch's version might have earned a much better reputation.

Comment:
¬†@jmo5755¬† Here's the thing about that though, Blade Runner 2049 received critical acclaim and Oscar's attention, still didn't do well at the Box Office enough though to warrant following through with another entry. 

Despite it, in my opinion, being the perfect sequel and a cinematic masterpiece, it didn't make much money...which is kind of shocking if I'm being honest. 

Denis has proven many times over that he is a very capable and talented director, even more so than Christopher Nolan. Money speaks over everything however, if Dune doesn't make enough waves despite it being a pandemic which is highly unfair to the film, they will not make a sequel because there's no point. 

They are really wanting this to be the next blockbuster franchise, they want it to be the Lord of the Rings of Science Fiction, the critically acclaimed, perfect adaptation that makes over a billion at the box office, etc. That is what they want out of this. 

If it is anything less, they will not make Part II and they will not adapt the rest of the series (which I really wish would bloody happen already.) 

So....no pressure to this film or anything, it has a lot of expectations.

Comment:
‚Äã¬†Iron *Fe*¬† Nah, I don't think it will be all that bad. Sure, things are different. That doesn't mean it'll be bad. Don't forget, they have 1984, AND the sci-fi series to learn from. Not to mention the books.

Besides. Don't forget, 1984 wasn't perfect either. Sure, they had immaculate sets, REALLY good casting, and a kickass soundtrack. Seriously, I can listen to it for hours.

But! Leaving aside what it did right, it fell short in other areas. Look at the 2nd half of the movie...pacing was way off. Suddenly, "Hello I'm Muad' Dib" cool...one fast action sequence later, they are demanding the Emperor leave. One knife fight with sting/feyd later and it's pretty much the end of the film. 

They skip a TON of material and rely very heavily on voice over. Provided, I get that wasn't their original intention and correct me if I'm wrong but they could have fallen short on time/budget. 

But the main thing the film gets wrong is the world of Dune itself. I mean yeah it gets some of it right but barely scratches the surface. They skip over so much that many don't even understand the ultimate motives of each main player of the story. Or why Paul is NOT the hero of Dune.

That is why I'm hopeful for this new picture. Since they are slowing it down into separate films. They also claim to be trying to be more accurate to the books.

Although, I'd rather we get a Netflix/HBO series or something.

Comment:
The one produced and shown by the Sci-Fi network (I think), was actually pretty good in that it was far more faithful to the novel than the first iteration by David Lynch. I thought it was very well done with one HUGE thing that broke it for me. This might sound petty, but the still-suits in that production were like someone had torn apart a thin tent canvas that was colored with an outdoorsy green color in order to sow them into a suit. It was thin, out of place, and completely unbelievable as a Still-Suit.

But, that aside, it was very impressive in my opinion. However, while it exceeded in being more true to the novel, it lacked the style and "vibe" that David Lynch provided. In other words, I have great respect for the Sci-Fi's version, but, ultimately, it came off as a bit stale. 

I have high hopes that this new stab at the material will be great. The trailers are incredible. Ultimately, we will all have to wait and see.

Comment: Not many will realize it but, the music in the trailer, which is not used in the film itself, is an homage to the director Alejandro Jodorowsky. He was putting together a version of Dune in the late sixties that would have rivaled 2001 for sheer vision and psychedelic brilliance ( a documentary on the attempt to make it, called Jodorowsky's Dune is well worth watching.) Casting choices would have included Orson Welles as Baron Harkonen and Mick Jagger as Paul. The music was going to be provided by... Pink Floyd. Jodorowsky was never able to raise enough money for the project, and had to abandon it. Someof the designers he connected together: Brian Froud,  H. R. Gieger, went on to make Alien . I do think, Villeneuves inclusion of this music is an appropriate nod to that vision.

Comment: ¬†@vitaliyjuterbog8912¬† No point in turning a book into a film if you are going to adapt it 100% 'faithfully'. Not only is it arguably pointless but it is also somewhat impossible. Books have far more time (along with other liberties) than films do to tell their story/stories. In some cases it's a blessing because it forces a screenwriter and/or director to get creative to make up for the things they are forced to cut out as well as strip down unnecessary 'fluff' that doesn't really help develop the story/characters. Not to mention the obvious fact of a book has to rely on the reader's imagination, so it has to paint a vivid picture with words, whereas film is a visual medium so that bit is built in.

Comment:
¬†@Diax1324¬†  How can an opinion be 'not really true'??? You can say my opinion sucks but that would be your opinion , see how that works?
And if you are speaking to the one fact I pointed out, unless you are reading children's books or graphic novels that is MOSTLY true. 'Mostly' meaning that your average book contains only words to describe to you a picture so you may imagine it.... films obviously have this as a universally predetermined advantage/disadvantage (depending on how you look at it).
EDIT: Apologies if I come of as a dick in the first sentence... that was not my intention.
author: @johnnywhitsel1583

Comment:
¬†@Diax1324¬† College arguments don't hold much weight anymore, my friend (I say that with absolutely NO disrespect towards you or your time there - perhaps you are an exception, not the rule), especially with myself. But what are your sources for believing it can work? This is entirely subjective if it does but I would like to evaluate the films you were taught/studied that did work.

I believe you are also looking far too much into the part of my 'argument' where I said it is "somewhat impossible"... Perhaps you are not seeing the irony I intended there? The irony being that something is either pointless or it is not, it's a binary, not a spectrum. I figured you/anyone would see it is merely (again) opinion. That's another reason I want to see the films you are basing your argument on because I am fully ready to admit I am wrong (would be happy to in this case actually) for my own growth as an aspiring writer/director. Also, was your strawman quote intended to make me look as if I am some kind of neanderthal or something? ....because I was really trying to be respectful and cordial here.

My primary argument was: it is pointless in my honest opinion to 100% faithfully adapt a book to film. Everyone has already imagined this vast world created and everyone/thing in it to a T (especially the 'fanatics' of your work). They know the entire story and every detail in it... why put it on film if it's just the same damn thing but you risk pissing off it's fanbase by adapting such work that may or may not fit well on a visual medium or the director, screenwriter and/or a producer with too much power demands something be done in 'X' area (while still being totally faithful to the source) that totally fucks the whole thing over?

People who read books have already proven themselves to not be too lazy to use their imagination to bring this world to life in their head by following the recipe guide so you have basically seen it play out anyway lol (albeit, not really perfectly until your 2nd, 3rd or whatever read through). I personally just don't see the point. I would much rather go in knowing this is a director's vision of the main events, with all the fluff stripped out and possibly new, better material thrown in. Examples? -In Jaws and Jurassic Park some of the most beloved characters in the films were absolute shit human beings in the books and the films were better off for changing them. Also, it would be endlessly mocked if The Lost World (the JP sequel) film took the route of reviving Ian Malcolm the same way the book did (and yes, the book is mocked for doing it to this day).

As far as the trailer goes... you have me in utter agreement there, my man. I really, really want to love this movie so all they need to do is not screw it up by injecting politics, pointless plot lines and lackluster dialogue to keep me on board. I have not read the book(s) so whether they change anything is a moot point to me in this case (at least until after I do commit to reading it). But suffice to say... as of now I am fully ready to go to see this movie, I was the instant someone told me the book served as the inspiration for Warhammer 40K. Only thing left to do is rent/buy the original film and give it one or two watches before this comes out.

On a side note I am quite satisfied with the soundtrack thus far. Love that vocal swell while they are on a dropship of some sort looking down on (what I assume is) a Sandworm devouring something. PLEASE NO SPOILER REPLIES!

This actually comes up in the novels, set the shield too low and you cannot fight for very long but you are on the other hand immune to slow projectile weapons such as dart guns or thrown knives.

Either way it leads to people typically fighting with knives or swords and slowing down right before they hit to avoid triggering the shield. Admittedly it never explains why professional troops do not wear space tech plate armour  and wear rebreathers to make themselves immune to swords whilst keeping the shields tuned down to the maximum possible extent.

Comment:
¬†@brian2440¬† I'd argue it's rather well thought-out.

If the shield stopped everything regardless of speed - it's explained you would suffocate and be unable to eat/drink with it on. Some people like their shields on pretty much all the time.

It also does stop literally everything: having less to do with the material (metal or bone or  play dough can be turned) and more to do with the speed of the object.

It's actually explained in the books that a "civilized" sword fighter who is used to fighting against shields naturally slows their killing blows down to a crawl to trick the shields into letting them through - which can work against you if you're fighting someone un-shielded (muscle memory)

Hopefully it's demonstrated in the movies properly - but you really do have to very slowly push a blade through, or it won't work.

Comment:
‚Äã¬†@GodlessXVIII¬† Herbert's style is... unique. I definitely wouldn't count him among the masters of the written word: he very much lacks that human touch. At the same time, no other book than the original Dune gave me that feeling that I was reading something trulu spectacular, genuinely expanding my horizons. There is so much obscure stuff in it that would be enough for anybody to just drop the book the mere few first chapters in and yet in Dune you just can't put it down, even as you need to reread the same sentence twenty times before you think you've grasped at least the gist of what the author meant.

The charm does wear down the deeper you get into the sequels though. Part of me wishes I hadn't actually read beyond the first book.
author: @yarpen26

Comment: ¬†@blankreg2191¬† While the last two books weren't necessarily the better written ones, they were most certainly far better than the prequels written afterward, and they provided probably the most fantastic and satisfying ending that could've been contrived for all 7. Comment: ¬†@soulchowdown¬† The Foundation story is big, but every part of the story can be told visually. Dune is really mostly about Paul's inner struggle to channel the destiny he has inherited. Film is a terrible medium for exploring inner conflict, especially inner conflict as complex as what Paul faces. Look at all the voiceover that the original movie used, which is a terrible way to try to make up for that weakness of film as a medium. Dune is extremely hard to film. If it succeeds as an adaptation of the book, it will only do so through superb writing and acting. More likely it will be a visual story about the events of the book but that misses the heart of the book. But we might get lucky.

Comment:
¬†@dylana.9057¬† 
There was no way Dune part one could have a satisfying ending if it was faithful to the book. The middle of the book has Paul and Jessica running away into the desert to join the Fremen and the Harkonnens conquering the Atreides. If it were to end exactly like Book 1: Dune it would have Paul sitting in a tent with his mom grieving over his father's death. Dune is too long to fit in one movie but is also too dense to properly fit into the traditional narrative of a plot. Lord of the Rings is arguably just as anticlimactic but tries to recover from that by making the ending of each book/movie fit as a milestone into the journey of the fellowship. Which Dune is technically also doing. Villnueve's Dune is going to be a three-part epic, the same way LotR is a three-part epic.

Comment:
Bad news, I heard they made Kynes a black woman.  I don't care how much anyone "doesn't care" about the politics involved, it completely changes the dynamic of the story and it was done for brownie points...  

Hollywood in the year 2021 CANNOT make a decent film, it will be impossible because all they know how to do is double-down.  Anyone saying it will be a faithful adaptation is high on hopium, or has no standards in the first place.  LotR wasn't perfect, but it was a level I could appreciate, and now I believe we're too late in this timeline for it to ever happen to Dune in the same way.  Maybe 20 years ago, but not today.  
Just look at the issues with the Hobbit trilogy, but then adjust it for another 7 years of decay, and apply that sci-fi books are always adapted more poorly than fantasy, because it's a more niche audience and there's so much less experience doing it.  Not to mention the complexity of the story is a bit higher, the politics in LotR was relatively simple compared to Dune.  And it wasn't even simple, Dune is just that much more complex.  I don't think hollywood has the IQ to do it right if they wanted to.

Comment:
¬†@amjiva¬†  I don't know much about the director except that everyone loves him, but I do know that a good director does not make a movie.  If it was up to the director alone, Lynch's Dune would've probably been just about right and there would be no need for a new one, save maybe for the newer special effects.  The studio, producers, etc can all have way too much pull and ruin everything.  

That being said, there is no scenario where you can have the Fremen culture take orders from a woman and make it seem plausible.  Hyper-traditional societies just don't work like that.  Not to mention, it eliminates a primary connection between Paul and Chani.

author: @shriedfrimp

Comment:
You'll get so addicted, I'm happy for you. Everything that has to do with Dune, is intoxicating.

I first saw Lynch's movie, in early 90's, right after Romania overthrew communism. Liked it a lot, memory id fuzy though if I saw it on TV or theaters.
Then I went to highschool and around '93 I got my hands on Dune2, the grandfather of all RTS games. Couldn't stop playing and wanted to find out more about who Atreides were, etc. Naturally I went and played Dune I.

Read Dune around '94 or '95, they only started to translate the books into romanian. Couldn't stop, a friend had all books up until Emperor, so I chain read them all. And then I had to wait, screaming, for the only editure in the land that owned the rights to get off their asses and translate and publish the rest.

Around 2002 found myself in US, in a bookstore, and my eyes fell on a shelf, filled with ALL Dune books up until that time. Bought them all, happy that I could now read them as they were originally written. Trust me, as someone that has a firm grasp on 3 different languages, things get lost in translation. When it comes to written works, best if you read them in original tongue, if you can.

Anyway, I hope you get addicted, is one good thing to be addicted to :).

Comment: Dune IS a weird story, but only the details are weird.  The underlying skeleton is a story that is as old as history itself: family is unseated and gets its domain and property taken away, scion of the family rebuilds and becomes stronger, gets revenge.  For a book written in 1965, you'll see that many of the details actually form the basis for much of sci fi today. Comment:
>The movie begins with Duncan Idaho arriving in Arrakis and meeting the Fremen.

>The first act is set in Caladan and ends with the Atreides arriving in Arrakis. The second act follows the Harkonnen raid. The third act centers on Paul and Jessica meeting the Fremen.

>Duke Leto is not killed by the poison capsule given to him by Dr. Yueh; Rabban publically executes him after his failed attempt on Baron Harkonnen‚Äôs life.

>Lady Jessica is a skilled fighter and uses the Weirding Way several times during the Harkonnen raid and their encounter with the Fremen.

>Gurney Halleck is taken prisoner by the Harkonnen during the raid. The plan is allegedly to open part 2 with his escape into the desert and reunion with Paul and Jessica.

>Paul and Jessica are rescued by Duncan and Liet Kynes after the Harkonnen raid. Duncan sacrifices himself to hold off the Saudaukar scouts pursuing them while Kynes helps Paul and Jessica to escape and instructs them to seek out the Fremen.

>Kynes is fatally stabbed by a Sardaukar soldier and they both fall into a ravine. After defiantly rejecting the Emperor‚Äôs authority, Kynes attracts a sandworm that devours both of them.

>Paul is aware that the Bene Gesserit engineered the prophecy of Muad‚ÄôDib to control the Fremen and decides to use it to rally them into an army against the Emperor.

>Paul has visions of Chani all the way back in Caladan. When they meet, she thinks little of him. After Paul earns the Fremen‚Äôs trust, he tells her about his visions and she ultimately reciprocates his feelings.

>Kynes is Chani's mother in this version, and the father is implied to be Stilgar.

>Stilgar remains mistrustful of Paul and Jessica as they ingrain themselves to the Fremen. When Jessica announces her plan to drink from the Water of Life, he believes it to be a coup, and his enforcer Jamis challenges Paul to a knife duel.

>Paul defeats Jamis, but is wounded in the process. Chani nurses him back to health, and they have sex.

>The movie ends with Jessica drinking from the Water of Life and Paul adopting the title of ‚ÄúMuad‚ÄôDib‚Äù and declaring war on the Harkonnen.

>Feyd-Reutha and the Emperor are mentioned, but do not appear. Princess Irulan neither appears nor is she mentioned. All will appear in the sequel Prophet of Dune. 

>Some additional action scenes, mostly knife fights and action beats during the Harkonnen raid.

>No internal monologues.

Comment:
I was lucky enough to see one of 5 "test cuts" of the original David Lynch Dune in 1984 in Los Angeles, a cut that virtually no one has ever seen.  It was a 5 hour cut with a 15 intermission and it was one of the most epic things I've ever seen in my life.  The studio RUINED what should have been a masterpiece, because I saw the 2 and a half hours they cut out!  

So, technically, the David Lynch version was the first one to do it justice.  If this one is better than the 5 hour DUNE I saw, then it will be truly epic.
author: @lsc9x2

Comment: ¬†@lsc9x2¬† Are you saying there is, somewhere, in the dark corner of a warehouse, a cut that is 5hrs long? How come noone has started a hunt for that thing!
author: @Zoggizzle

Comment: ¬†@Zoggizzle¬† My guess is that the extended cuts were shelved and then either lost or destroyed.  All I can tell you is that the Dune I saw in the 1980s was EPIC.  It really was stunning, and I consider it a work of art.  When they cut out that 2 1/2 hours, almost all of the love story, and most of how Paul came to lead the Fremen was cut.  The movie that was left was just a skeleton of a plot, and pretty awful because they cut all the parts that tied everything together.  I can see why people didn't like the 1984 movie and I've NEVER forgiven the studio for losing that cut!

Comment:
¬†@paigewhitfield3624¬† You have 2 great Noble Houses, House Atreides and House Harkonnen, in a conflict over their places in the Landsraad (noble houses collectives). Duke Leto II Atreides receive planet Arrakis - the only known planet in the universe that has Sand Worms, which are responsible for "creating" spice/melange, powerful narcotic that can prolong human life, boosts psychical powers. Every fraction needs it, sisters Bene Geserit (to boost their psychical powers, rituals etc.), Guild Navigators needs it (to navigate trough hyperspace without smashing all over some planets, rocks, etc. Simply: "He who controls the spice, controls the universe" :) Sadly for Leto II, receiving Dune from Emperor hands is a trap. Emperor is afraid of house Atreides rise in power and respect among the Landsraad, so he decides to get rid off them by using Harkonnens. 
There is also a another plot that includes Bene Geserit eugenic program to create male version of themself, a "Kwisatz Haderach" - he would have all the powers that typical BG has but also he would be able to see inside the "darkness" that BG cannot look. They want to use it as their to seize total control. That "chosen" kid supposed to be born from Duke Leto II daughter and Baron Harkonnen nephew, Feyd Rautha. Sadly for the BG, Lady Jessica, Duke Leto concubine (and also BG), instead of giving him daughter (as eugenic program planned) gives him son he so badly wanted and thus fucks up BG plan. Paul is the "ultimate goal" of BG eugenic program born earlier than sisters planned it and as time goes they will understand that they can't control him and make him their tool :)

Comment: Let me put it like this: even if the movie is thousand times more amazing than the trailer - the books are hundred times more mindblowing than any movie could ever be. Those books transcend anything that was ever written. They make best books you ever read look like "Twilight". The world described in books - exactly like you see in the trailer, but much harsher, there is no sense of epic - people die and it's real, not heroic. The books are very intelligent about - book 1 - make Paul into an icon - book 2 - destroy this image - show ugly underbelly of actual righteous and good becoming rich politicians as a result of their coup. In book 3 and 4 designs and ideas, descriptions of universe, religion, countries, war, ideologies, humanity... there is nothing like Dune, ok? And if this director did it right we waited for those movies almost sixty years since Dune was published in 1965. It will blow your mind anyone could think like this in those times you know from utter prejudice, sexism, misogyny and racism.

>Gurney Halleck is taken prisoner by the Harkonnen during the raid. The plan is allegedly to open part 2 with his escape into the desert and reunion with Paul and Jessica.

>Paul and Jessica are rescued by Duncan and Liet Kynes after the Harkonnen raid. Duncan sacrifices himself to hold off the Saudaukar scouts pursuing them while Kynes helps Paul and Jessica to escape and instructs them to seek out the Fremen.

>Kynes is fatally stabbed by a Sardaukar soldier and they both fall into a ravine. After defiantly rejecting the Emperor‚Äôs authority, Kynes attracts a sandworm that devours both of them.

>Paul is aware that the Bene Gesserit engineered the prophecy of Muad‚ÄôDib to control the Fremen and decides to use it to rally them into an army against the Emperor.

>Paul has visions of Chani all the way back in Caladan. When they meet, she thinks little of him. After Paul earns the Fremen‚Äôs trust, he tells her about his visions and she ultimately reciprocates his feelings.

>Kynes is Chani's mother in this version, and the father is implied to be Stilgar.

>Stilgar remains mistrustful of Paul and Jessica as they ingrain themselves to the Fremen. When Jessica announces her plan to drink from the Water of Life, he believes it to be a coup, and his enforcer Jamis challenges Paul to a knife duel.

>Paul defeats Jamis, but is wounded in the process. Chani nurses him back to health, and they have sex.

>The movie ends with Jessica drinking from the Water of Life and Paul adopting the title of ‚ÄúMuad‚ÄôDib‚Äù and declaring war on the Harkonnen.

>Feyd-Reutha and the Emperor are mentioned, but do not appear. Princess Irulan neither appears nor is she mentioned. All will appear in the sequel Prophet of Dune. 

>Some additional action scenes, mostly knife fights and action beats during the Harkonnen raid.

>No internal monologues.

¬†@Zeon081¬† I could write for hours why it is. The original Blade Runner is a mess, because Ridley Scott did not know what he did back then, didn't understand the script, had constant fights with the actors and the crew, and did not have enough material to work with when he entered the editing room. In short he was and is an idiot.
And that's why the most memorable scene (maybe even the only memorable scene) is a brilliant improvised moment at the end. Most of the rest of the movie is either boring or confusing. Don't get me wrong, I still like that messy movie, because it is one of the luckiest accidents in cinema history. But it is simply foolish to think that Blade Runner comes even close to the well thought out, directed, paced, written, acted and filmed movie that Blade Runner 2049 objectively is.
author: @ragismrotzrochen5776

Comment: It is an example of something called "Archeofuturism."  The culture, traditions, and social model are bound in something that is transcendent and timeless. Comment:
>The movie begins with Duncan Idaho arriving in Arrakis and meeting the Fremen.

>The first act is set in Caladan and ends with the Atreides arriving in Arrakis. The second act follows the Harkonnen raid. The third act centers on Paul and Jessica meeting the Fremen.

>Duke Leto is not killed by the poison capsule given to him by Dr. Yueh; Rabban publically executes him after his failed attempt on Baron Harkonnen‚Äôs life.

>Lady Jessica is a skilled fighter and uses the Weirding Way several times during the Harkonnen raid and their encounter with the Fremen.

>Gurney Halleck is taken prisoner by the Harkonnen during the raid. The plan is allegedly to open part 2 with his escape into the desert and reunion with Paul and Jessica.

>Paul and Jessica are rescued by Duncan and Liet Kynes after the Harkonnen raid. Duncan sacrifices himself to hold off the Saudaukar scouts pursuing them while Kynes helps Paul and Jessica to escape and instructs them to seek out the Fremen.

>Kynes is fatally stabbed by a Sardaukar soldier and they both fall into a ravine. After defiantly rejecting the Emperor‚Äôs authority, Kynes attracts a sandworm that devours both of them.

>Paul is aware that the Bene Gesserit engineered the prophecy of Muad‚ÄôDib to control the Fremen and decides to use it to rally them into an army against the Emperor.

>Paul has visions of Chani all the way back in Caladan. When they meet, she thinks little of him. After Paul earns the Fremen‚Äôs trust, he tells her about his visions and she ultimately reciprocates his feelings.

>Kynes is Chani's mother in this version, and the father is implied to be Stilgar.

>Stilgar remains mistrustful of Paul and Jessica as they ingrain themselves to the Fremen. When Jessica announces her plan to drink from the Water of Life, he believes it to be a coup, and his enforcer Jamis challenges Paul to a knife duel.

>Paul defeats Jamis, but is wounded in the process. Chani nurses him back to health, and they have sex.

>The movie ends with Jessica drinking from the Water of Life and Paul adopting the title of ‚ÄúMuad‚ÄôDib‚Äù and declaring war on the Harkonnen.

>Feyd-Reutha and the Emperor are mentioned, but do not appear. Princess Irulan neither appears nor is she mentioned. All will appear in the sequel Prophet of Dune. 

>Some additional action scenes, mostly knife fights and action beats during the Harkonnen raid.

>No internal monologues.

Comment:
Ottee2 when making a dune movie you have several options. 1: make it over 3 hours long. 2: make it extremely condensed and impenetrable to anyone not already familiar with the source material. 3: cut out tons of content so you get generic space action with a Dune skin on top of it.

Dune is not Starwars, Dune is Shakespeare. Even Frank Herbert wrote a script for the movie and it came in at over 3 hours (everyone who tried had the same result). That‚Äôs why Lynch‚Äôs was so compact and filled with exposition dumps (it was 3 hours crushed into 2). This is why the Miniseries are far superior to the movie because they have the time to breath. Now if you redid the mini series with an actual budget I would be excited but I can‚Äôt see this being good. Considering the few shots of the Baron (covered in oil) I feel this is going to be a bigger budget remake of Lynch‚Äôs movie

Comment: Read it twice.  First pass it can be hard to keep track of everything (even if you're smart); it can be a legit slog.  Use the glossary and read the appendices.  The story itself is an absolute epic; but it can be a little obscured by terminess and complexity.  It get's way more enjoyable when you're no longer burdened by the mountain of details.  I've read it a couple of dozen times and was still picking up details on my 3rd and 4th pass.  Also, this was Herbert's first book after having 26 jobs unrelated to writing.  He's not a terribly good writer and the voicing of characters, in particular, is rather weak.  But if you can soldier through some of the shortcomings you'll be rewarded with a futuristic Homerian epic that is incomparably ambitious.

Comment:
¬†@vicentekokaly322¬† The original quote mentions 'refrain', which means a set of lines that are repeated in a song or a chant. This doesn't sound like what Paul would say, especially given his reserved nature and his intelligence / personality. It sounds more like something that the common people would say or sing after Paul became Emperor.

Actually, Yueh was the reason why Paul survived. He cut the seatbelt that Jessica was wearing (in the ornithopter), then arranged for Duncan Idaho to show up right at the drop site. It was clear that his betrayal of the Atreides was not 100% complete. Without his betrayal and his subsequent actions, the Atreides would have dug down into Arrakis for a war against the Harkonnen and Sardaukar legions. It would have been a future where Paul would not have become the Messiah, and he would have remained as Duke, and only as the Duke. The Fremen would have only allied with him, nothing more.

Comment: ¬†@Loccyster¬† I see your point, but my contention is that if people are protective of the Arabic influence in the novel being included on film and of Arabic culture not being demonized then we should show some respect towards those concerns as they are not without precedent. Arabic influence in novels has been erased in popular Hollywood films before, Star Wars being an example and it's far easier to demonize a group of people if the stories in our pop culture have no positive characters of their origin and if the language and culture in question are associated only with things of a threatening or inferior nature-as is too often case with Islamic and Arabic people in our popular culture. So even if what the commentator is saying isn't entirely accurate, I think the general critique is warranted  and there is no need to be so contemptuous or dismissive in your comments. A big film like this is something which will undoubtedly have an impact on an audience's psyche  and it seems like the Arabic influence in the novel has been largely, omitted in the film by the look of the trailer.

¬†@jakefastf¬†  Regardless of whether you're tolling or not, it is prudent to state that Dune directly influenced George Lucas when he was writing Star Wars. In fact Frank Herbert, the author of Dune, accused Lucas of ripping off Dune when Star Wars was made.

The first of many Dune books came out in 1965, more than 10 years before Star Wars. SO yeah, try doing some research first before thinking you know what you're talking about. 

And in terms of "the look", people should read the damn Dune novel(s). Herbert is extremely detailed about the Dune universe to the point where you can use the novel as set design for the movie. So any resemblance to contemporary sci-fi is because the latter is inspired by the former.

Comment:
A beginning is a very delicate time.

Know then that it is the year ten thousand and one, ninety one. The known universe is ruled by the Padishah Emperor, Shaddam the fourth, my father.

In this time the most precious substance in the universe is the Spice Melange. The Spice extends life, the Spice expands consciousness, the Spice is vital to space travel. The Spacing Guild and its Navigators who the Spice has mutated over four thousand years use the orange Spice gas, which gives them the ability to fold space, that is travel to any part of the universe without moving.

Oh yes, I forgot to tell you, the Spice exists on only one planet in the entire universe, a desolate, dry planet, with vast deserts. Hidden away within the rocks of these deserts are a people known as the Fremen, who have long held a prophecy that a man would come, a messiah, who would lead them to true freedom.

The planet is Arrakis, also known as Dune.
